We recommended that management ensure that:
a. No additional cash advance shall be granted to an accountable officer without full liquidation of his/her previous cash advance;
b. Cash advances other than for travels are duly supported with certification from the Accountant that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books;
c. Liquidations of cash advances are made within the reglementary period; and
d. Ensure that all cash advances are liquidated at the end of each year.

We recommended that Management:
a. exert effort in determining the claimants/creditors of the ₱2,865,473.74 recorded as Other Payables to ensure its validity and existence; 
b. reclassify the Other Payables with negative balances totaling ₱185,934.99 as Receivables and enforce collection thereof.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to:
effect the proposed reclassification entry as follows:
restate the financial statements to reflect the proposed reclassification entry;
conduct a thorough review of the Lapsing Schedule of PPE to identify PPE accounts recorded in lump-sum amounts and lacking specific details such as quantity and unit cost;
retrieve and examine the pertinent documents to determine whether the individual items fall below the capitalization threshold and, if so, prepare the necessary reclassification entry/ies;
hereafter, ensure that all procured PPE items are reflected in the lapsing schedule with complete details to support clear identification and proper classification;
provide an additional disclosure in the notes to the financial statements regarding the change in accounting policy, in compliance with Paragraph 34 of IPSAS 3; and
refrain from taking on tasks that fall outside the core responsibilities of the Accounting Office and instead assign them to the appropriate departments. In turn, allocate relevant accounting-related duties—such as the preparation of the PPE schedule—to the accounting personnel.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to:
identify and implement targeted training programs and capacity-building initiatives, particularly those aimed at advancing technical proficiency such as Microsoft Word and Excel and other interventions designed to enhance the functional capabilities of accounting personnel, thereby improving the accuracy and efficiency of financial reporting and expediting the reconciliation of remittances to the appropriate government agencies;
ensure the timely updating and reconciliation of employee records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth to facilitate the accurate remittance and proper settlement of outstanding balances from prior years;
review the monthly premiums deducted from payroll/DVs for GSIS, Pag-IBIG and Philhealth, to ensure that the amounts withheld match the amounts due for remittance each month; and
strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 8291, RA No. 9769 and Revised IRR of RA No. 7875, to avoid administrative sanctions and ensure proper fulfillment of the Municipality’s obligations to the concerned agencies.

We therefore recommended that the LCE direct the MENRO-Designate to:
strengthen programming by equipping himself of the needed skills to identify compliance-driven priorities in the budget cycle and aligning them with available resources, to promote proactive, safe, and standards-based implementation of the SWMP;
ensure that the budget allocation for salaries and wages of Job Order garbage collectors is sufficient to cover the actual number of personnel employed, thereby supporting uninterrupted operations;
include in the SWMP the provision for appropriate personal protective equipment for all collectors and personnel directly involved in the handling, collection, and transport of solid waste, to ensure that they are adequately protected, promote occupational safety, and minimize exposure to health risks; and
coordinate with the Municipal Health Officer or other appropriate agencies to facilitate the conduct of training programs aimed at enhancing the safety awareness, technical competencies, and proper handling practices of garbage collectors and utility workers, in line with occupational health standards and the requirements of RA No. 9003;

We recommended to Management the following:
Consider transferring the PPEs to the recipient offices by accomplishing the Property Transfer Receipts (PTRs) which will be the basis of Municipal Accountant in preparing the following journal entries to drop the items of PPE from the books of accounts of LGU Luna, Isabela;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the misclassification of accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries (AJE) to correct the balance of the appropriate accumulated depreciation and government equity accounts reported in the financial statements in line with Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1 and Section 111 of P.D. No. 1445;
The Municipal Accountant coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to obtain adequate information on the completed infrastructure projects and immediately reclassify these into the proper infrastructure assets accounts consistent with Paragraph 14 of IPSAS 17 and COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;
The Inventory Committee immediately conduct physical count and henceforth submit the RPCPPE within the deadline set by the Commission to the Auditor’s Office which is not later than January 31 of each year;
Direct the Municipal General Services Officer Designate to prepare the Report on Local Road Network, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with a complete description and cost segregation of road components for all road projects;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements, prepare the Local Road Network Ledger Card, and ensure the timely recording of completed road projects and recompute the depreciation for Calendar Year 2024 to reflect the accurate asset valuation and reliable financial reporting;
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer prepare and regularly update the PPELCs and PCs to ensure the integrity of property custodianship and that adequate internal control is adapted in accordance with pertinent provisions of the NGAS Manual for LGUs.
Initiate and prioritize the registration and/or transfer of the titles of land in the name of LGU Luna, Isabela to have conclusive evidence of ownership and to fully protect the interest of the Municipality in adherence to Section 39(2) of P.D. No. 1445 and Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the concerned offices for the reconciliation of the unaccounted beginning balance of Land and prepare the necessary adjustments to come up with a reliable and accurate financial information.

We recommended to Management the following:
Issue Demand Letter to the concerned individual and exhaust all possible remedies to collect the Receivable balance of ₱368,061.40;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the adjusting journal entries to correct the misclassification of receivables from an individual who is no longer connected with the agency in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 to come up with an accurate and reliable financial information;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to secure the necessary documents, if deemed appropriate, to support the request for write-off of the dormant receivables account and follow the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts provided by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to thereafter recognize allowance for impairment on the Other Receivable balance pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 . The amount of impairment shall be based on collectability of receivable balances and based on evaluation of such factors as aging of accounts, collection experiences of the agency, expected loss experiences and identified doubtful accounts.

