2. We have reiterated the following recommendations:

The Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory of all Property, Plant and Equipment of the municipality in order to determine their existence and condition;
The GSO to maintain property cards per category of PPE;
The Accounting Unit to maintain complete property ledger cards for all PPE owned by the agency;
The GSO Designate and Accounting Unit to exert effort in reconciling their records from time to time;
 The GSO Designate and Accounting unit to effect the proper documentation and immediate disposition of all unserviceable property; and 
The Accounting unit to exert effort in locating or producing the documents to support the legitimacy of the unreconciled PPE account balances and thereafter, strengthen the control over documentation of all financial transactions.

3. We have recommended that management:

Require the concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances to immediately liquidate/refund/settle their accounts.  Otherwise, the penalty prescribed under Section 128 of PD 1445 shall be enforced and appropriate administrative proceedings shall likewise be constituted;
Cause or order the withholding of any money claims against the concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances until they have fully liquidated/settled their accounts;
Ensure full liquidation of cash advances at the end of the year;
Refrain from granting cash advances to a single payee in behalf of others to encourage prompt liquidation and to be able to monitor who are not entitled to additional cash advances; and
Adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 to avoid misappropriation of the excess/unutilized cash advances and possible loss of liquidation documents.

We recommended management to:

[a] conduct regular reconciliation of records and reports to be undertaken by the Treasury and Accounting Offices at the end of each month or at least quarterly prior to the preparation of financial reports to avoid accumulation of unreconciled variances;

[b] effect the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts.

We recommended management to:

[a] account all the noted variances between the books of accounts and the inventory report and continue to reconcile until these items will be fully identified;

[b] investigate the recorded and unrecorded PPE items in the books of accounts.  Obtain sufficient proof of their existence and effect adjustments in the books of accounts, if necessary;

[c] provide for motor pool wherein unserviceable properties as well as assets still use for operations could be properly secured and safeguarded against the elements of wear and tear;

[d] create an Appraisal and Disposal Committee who will be responsible for the evaluation of the reasonable resale value of the unserviceable properties listed in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and the immediate disposal of said items; and

[e] promptly cause the sale of the unserviceable motor vehicles thru public auction in accordance with COA Circular No. 86-264.

We recommend that management be required to:

[a] Ensure that the beneficiaries are the ones who will receive the cash, if not, a letter consent of the beneficiary authorizing the kin to receive in their behalf;

[b] If in case the distribution is to be undertaken in the barangay, it should be witnessed by (1) President of Senior Citizen of that barangay, (2) at least one barangay official and (3) from any employee of the MSWDO;

[c] Require the concerned employee of the MSWDO who was designated to distribute the fund during the first and second quarter of CY 2018 to explain why these afore-cited allegations occurred;

[d] Require the accountable officer to refund the amount in question; and

[e] Conduct investigation of similar incident and appropriate sanction/s be imposed to MSWDO official and other accessory personnel, if warranted.

